Curtain
“Please,” Queen Elwynn begged, “don't send her away! She's just a child!” King Ice sat on his throne, gazing down at his wife, with his royal advisors standing by her side. His wife had given birth to a daughter. At the thought of this, King Ice couldn't help but furrow his brow.
The infant girl looked just like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, and a few strands of blue hair woven in. King Ice thought having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only sons before.
“You have two options: either kill this child, or abandon her in the wilderness. Elwynn, this is your punishment.” He spat out her name with venom, as if it were poison itself. He always did this.
The Kingdom of Glacia wasn't always a unified kingdom. It had once been divided into two parts, the north and the south. The north was a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom overflowing with magical powers. Due to the north's greed, the two kingdoms had been embroiled in endless wars until the south proposed a ceasefire.
When the south was at its wit's end, members of the royal family were willing to sacrifice everything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed that the only princess be married off to the north, become the queen of the north, and give birth to a son as the future king. After that, the south would merge with the north to establish a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Elwynn was thus married to Prince Akkur.
“Please, my king, for the sake of my child's safety, you can do anything to me, lock me up, exile me, or even kill me.” Princess Elwynn begged, holding her child tightly in her arms.
King Ice looked down at the queen with a look of disgust. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would have a shred of mercy for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him in his most desolate times, and borne him children.
“Alright. The child can stay in the palace.” Upon hearing King Ice's words, the queen let out a sigh of relief. “However,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisors and Queen Elwynn both displayed expressions of terror. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the ground. “Yes, my king.” She bowed.
King Ice ordered royal advisors to take the queen's daughter to an empty room belonging to Elwynn. After completion, he ordered the guards to take Elwynn to the public execution ground.
When the guards escorted her to the execution ground, citizens saw their only queen - also the kindest queen - about to be executed and felt extremely angry. Some people cried, some shouted and tried to attack the guards, and some wondered why this had to happen; but they all had the same question.
“Let her go!”
“Why are they treating her this way?”
As Elwynn approached the wooden column, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the fire punishment. The former queen Elwynn was to be burned alive. No one should be subjected to fire punishment, not even criminals. In the Kingdom of Glacia, fire punishment was the cruelest punishment.
Ai Er Wen was bound to a wooden column, and the king began to tell the queen how she had betrayed them all. The people of the Kingdom of Glacia refused to believe it, nor would they ever accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden column, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
“Kali, survive!” This marked the end of the life of Queen Ai Er Wen.
The hall was deathly silent.
In the cold palace's south wing, from the room on the far left, came the endless “tick-tock” sound. Past servants were always curious about what was inside, but they were too afraid to get close. The maids walked around the hall, whispering to each other, spreading rumors. Some believed that the ice king's deceased wife Ai Er Wen was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They were all wrong. Ai Fei thought to himself as he walked towards the south wing, servants walking along the wall, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were many rumors about her, because she was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocking on the door, "Kali, are you inside?" Avery spoke softly in front of the complex door, which was decorated with snowflakes and crown patterns, a symbol of the royal family.
She didn't know if she would let him in this time either, and it was quite different from before. I still have the bruises from last time. Avery remembered this incident and couldn't help but laugh. At the time, Kali threw a book at him, but when she saw who it was, she immediately apologized.
A sound came from the room, as if she was saying she couldn't go anywhere else, just staying there.
"Can I come in?" Avery asked, forgetting the consequences of uninvited entry last time.
The room again echoed with a faint sound, as if it was saying "come in". Ai Fei felt a chill, unsure if it was due to the cold or the voice. Although he had been there for a long time, hearing the sound from the room still made him feel a bit strange.
"I'm in." Ai Fei said slowly, opening the door. By normal human standards, the scene in the room was quite unusual, but it was also expected. The room was covered in paper. Books were scattered all over the floor, and the table was broken. There were many ice sculptures in the room. There was no window, and there was hardly any light. The room was even colder than other parts of the palace (which revealed a lot). The room looked like it had been hit by a blizzard, with everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up on the bed, wrapped in a blanket, and reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Ai Fei sat down next to Kali's bed and asked.
